    "severity": "MEDIUM",
    "category": "dos-surface",
    "location": "scripts/ai_agent_bridge/openai_proxy.py:31",
    "description": "The request schema accepts arbitrarily large `messages` and content values, then flattens them and passes the result into subprocesses. A client can send a very large JSON body that consumes memory/CPU during validation and prompt construction, or triggers oversized subprocess inputs/argv, tying up the service until timeout. Add request/body and prompt-size limits before crossing the subprocess boundary."
  },
  {
    "id": "prompt-passed-via-argv",
    "severity": "MEDIUM",
    "category": "security",
    "location": "scripts/ai_agent_bridge/openai_proxy.py:153",
    "description": "Gemini, Claude, and Hermes prompts are passed as command-line arguments (`--prompt=...`, positional prompt, `--oneshot=...`). Request contents can therefore be exposed through process listings and can fail with argv-size limits for large prompts. Pass prompt text through stdin or a temporary file consistently instead of argv."
  },
  {
    "id": "stream-requests-silently-ignored",
    "severity": "LOW",
    "category": "spec-compliance",
    "location": "scripts/ai_agent_bridge/openai_proxy.py:285",
    "description": "The request model allows extra fields, but `chat_completions` does not inspect unsupported OpenAI options such as `stream: true`; it returns a normal non-streaming 200 response. Many OpenAI-compatible clients rely on streaming semantics and will mis-handle this. Reject unsupported streaming requests with a clear 400/422 error until streaming is implemented."
  }
